# 9front grep(1) — pattern search

## Synopsis

    grep [-bchiLlnsv] [-e] pattern | -f patternfile [file ...]
    g [flags] pattern [file ...]

## Description

grep searches input files (stdin by default) for lines matching a Plan 9
regular expression (see regexp(6)).  A newline in the pattern acts as an
alternation operator (lowest precedence, same as |).

## Options

    -b    Don't buffer output; write each line as it is found.
    -c    Print only a count of matching lines per file.
    -e    Treat the next argument as the pattern (useful for patterns
          beginning with -).
    -f    Read patterns from a file, one per line.
    -h    Suppress file name headers on output lines.
    -i    Case-insensitive match (folds both pattern and input to lower case;
          prints original-case lines).
    -L    Print only names of files with NO matching lines (converse of -l).
    -l    Print only names of files that have at least one matching line.
    -n    Prefix each matching line with its line number in the file.
    -s    Silent: produce no output; use exit status only.
    -v    Invert: print lines that do NOT match.

## Output

When more than one file is given, each output line is prefixed with the
file name.  To force this tagging with a single file, add /dev/null as an
extra argument.

## Exit status

Null (success) if any lines were selected; non-null if no lines matched or
an error occurred.

## g wrapper

g invokes grep -n and forces file-name tagging.  With no file arguments it
recursively searches the current directory for common source file extensions
(*.c *.h *.rc *.go *.py *.awk *.sh *.txt and many others).  Passing -n to
g suppresses the recursive search and reads stdin or the named files only.

## Regular expressions (Plan 9 regexp(6))

Metacharacters: . * + ? [] () | ^ $
  .       any character except newline
  ^       beginning of line
  $       end of line
  [abc]   character class
  [^abc]  negated class (never matches newline)
  a-z     range inside []
  e*      zero or more
  e+      one or more
  e?      zero or one
  e1e2    concatenation
  e1|e2   alternation
  (e)     grouping

Backslash escapes a metacharacter or the delimiter.  No POSIX named
classes; no \d \w etc.

## Examples

Search for 'foo' in all .c files:
    grep foo *.c

Case-insensitive search, show line numbers:
    grep -in 'error' log

Print only file names containing 'TODO':
    grep -l TODO *.c *.h

Invert: lines not matching blank:
    grep -v '^$' file

Count matches per file:
    grep -c pattern *.txt

Use -e for a pattern that looks like a flag:
    grep -e -v file

Read patterns from a file:
    grep -f patterns.txt corpus.txt

Recursive source search with g:
    g 'malloc' 

Force file-name tags on a single file:
    grep pattern file /dev/null

## Differences from POSIX grep

**Regexp engine:** Uses Plan 9 regexp(6), not ERE or BRE.  There are no
POSIX character classes ([[:alpha:]] etc.), no \d \w \s \b shorthand, no
backreferences in patterns, and no look-ahead/look-behind.  Alternation is
| (as in ERE), not the BRE \|.  Parentheses for grouping are ( ) not \( \).

**Newline as alternation:** A literal newline inside the pattern string is
treated as | with lowest precedence.  POSIX does not define this behavior.

**No -E / -G / -P flags:** There is no -E (extended regexp), -G (basic
regexp), or -P (Perl regexp) option.  The single regexp dialect is always
Plan 9 ERE-like.

**No -r / --recursive flag:** grep itself has no recursive directory search.
Use the g(1) wrapper for recursive searches over source trees.

**No -w / -x flags:** Word-boundary (-w) and full-line (-x) matching flags
are absent.  Approximate them with regexp anchors: \b is unavailable; use
patterns like '(^|[^a-zA-Z0-9_])word([^a-zA-Z0-9_]|$)' or the ^ $ anchors.

**No -A / -B / -C context flags:** There is no way to print N lines of
context before or after a match.

**No -o flag:** Cannot print only the matching portion of each line.

**-i case folding:** Implemented by folding to lower case in the ASCII range
only (a byte loop: c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z').  Non-ASCII case folding is not
performed.

**-b flag:** On POSIX, -b prints the byte offset of each match.  On 9front,
-b means don't buffer output (write each result line immediately).  These
are completely different behaviors.

**Exit status:** Exits with the string "no matches" (non-null) when no lines
match, null on success — consistent with POSIX but expressed as a Plan 9
exit string rather than a numeric code.

